english:
  title: Royal Rescript Declining Lee Saek's Request to Resign as Left Docksal
  author: Jeon Nok-saeng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I consider that the Ten Thousand Matters of state grow exceedingly numerous, and wisdom alone cannot govern them. There is the office of Bearer of the Decree, which truly holds the vital post of uttering the sovereign's words and receiving their counsel. Because the responsibility attached to it is no trifle, we take great care in choosing the right man for it.

    Your nature is discerning and keen, your literary talent abundant and superior. From youth you inherited your father's way, and your name has traveled even to distant lands. Now you have gained the regard of all the scholars, becoming a standard for the Eastern Kingdom. Your learning is already comprehensive and far-reaching, and your counsel is worthy to illuminate the ruler's path.

    Thus have I regarded you with special favor, elevating you from humble station to great office. I have entrusted to you the role of my voice at my left and right, that your excellence might be manifest near and far. All matters of writing and words I have placed in your hands. Yet unexpectedly you speak of resignation. How can I fathom your true intention? Is it that my regard has not convinced you of my sincerity? Or have I failed to heed your counsel?

    But between ruler and subject, nothing should remain hidden. Why should we fear that our feelings cannot be understood? Moreover, if a subject seeks only his own comfort, how can this accord with righteousness? What wrong have I done you that you should harbor doubt toward me? Take to heart my meaning and apply yourself diligently to your office. Your petition for release cannot be granted.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Ten Thousand Matters' (万機) is a classical phrase referring to the comprehensive duties of imperial governance.
    - The 'Left Docksal' (左代言) was a high official position in Goryeo responsible for drafting royal documents and advising the throne.
    - Lee Saek (李穡, 1328-1396) was a distinguished Goryeo scholar-official and son of the renowned literatus Lee Inka.
